00:10:44.870 --> 00:10:47.810
and starches.

00:10:47.810 --> 00:10:50.380
INTERVIEWER: Glad
you enjoyed it.

00:10:50.380 --> 00:10:51.950
So I have actually a question.

00:10:51.950 --> 00:10:53.330
The name of the book is
"Paddle Your Own Canoe,"

00:10:53.330 --> 00:10:55.925
but this is actually a canoe
that's you've built yourself.

00:10:55.925 --> 00:10:57.175
NICK OFFERMAN: It is, in fact.

00:11:00.236 --> 00:11:01.042
Was that--

00:11:01.042 --> 00:11:03.000
INTERVIEWER: That was a
leading question, yeah.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:05.790
NICK OFFERMAN:
Grammatically speaking.

00:11:05.790 --> 00:11:07.730
Would you like to hear
a little bit about it?

00:11:07.730 --> 00:11:10.585
INTERVIEWER: Please.

00:11:10.585 --> 00:11:12.330
NICK OFFERMAN: Her
name is Huckleberry.

00:11:12.330 --> 00:11:15.560
My wife was doing a Broadway
show some years ago,

00:11:15.560 --> 00:11:20.730
and we don't live apart
for more than two weeks.

00:11:20.730 --> 00:11:23.390
That's a rule.

00:11:23.390 --> 00:11:25.810
Actors that work a lot,
which we're lucky enough

00:11:25.810 --> 00:11:30.330
to be sometimes, often
have their relationships

00:11:30.330 --> 00:11:32.600
suffer because they
go to play Frodo

00:11:32.600 --> 00:11:35.530
Baggins in New
Zealand for 18 months.

00:11:35.530 --> 00:11:36.550
Not naming any names.

00:11:39.760 --> 00:11:44.870
What I'm saying is I turned
down the role of Frodo Baggins

00:11:44.870 --> 00:11:46.897
to preserve my marriage.

00:11:46.897 --> 00:11:47.980
I made the right decision.

00:11:54.610 --> 00:11:56.750
I went with Megan to
live in New York, which

00:11:56.750 --> 00:11:58.070
I was very excited to do.

00:11:58.070 --> 00:12:00.860
And I had been looking
for an opportunity

00:12:00.860 --> 00:12:02.475
to build my first canoe.

00:12:02.475 --> 00:12:04.240
So I took a bag
of tools with me,

00:12:04.240 --> 00:12:07.420
and I built it in
Red Hook, Brooklyn.

00:12:07.420 --> 00:12:12.200
And it was one of the greatest
things I've ever gotten to do.

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:14.509
I highly recommend it.

00:12:14.509 --> 00:12:16.800
Although if you're going to
do it in this neighborhood,

00:12:16.800 --> 00:12:19.260
I'd go with an ocean kayak.

00:12:19.260 --> 00:12:23.490
LA is not a great
canoeing community.

00:12:23.490 --> 00:12:24.530
I learned the hard way.

00:12:24.530 --> 00:12:25.607
INTERVIEWER: Oh, I see.

00:12:25.607 --> 00:12:27.940
Well, they're opening up the
LA river, supposedly, for--

00:12:27.940 --> 00:12:30.250
NICK OFFERMAN: They
are, and it's neat.

00:12:30.250 --> 00:12:34.770
There's a cool
section to kayak on.

00:12:34.770 --> 00:12:39.210
Some of it looks very much like
where Danny Zuko raced Greased

00:12:39.210 --> 00:12:44.476
Lightnin' down the sides of
the LA river, which is badass.

00:12:44.476 --> 00:12:46.119
INTERVIEWER: Awesome.

00:12:46.119 --> 00:12:47.660
NICK OFFERMAN: Great
seeing you guys.

00:12:51.562 --> 00:12:53.520
INTERVIEWER: So you were
going to read a couple

00:12:53.520 --> 00:12:54.520
sections from your book.

00:12:54.520 --> 00:12:57.590
We don't have a lot of time,
so I figure, you can do that.

00:12:57.590 --> 00:13:00.400
And then we can basically
open up the questions

00:13:00.400 --> 00:13:01.205
from the audience

00:13:01.205 --> 00:13:03.250
NICK OFFERMAN: OK.

00:13:03.250 --> 00:13:07.300
The paddle, as well, is
my best paddle so far.

00:13:07.300 --> 00:13:11.100
It's Alaskan yellow cedar,
to answer your question,

00:13:11.100 --> 00:13:17.990
with accents of cherry inlaid
into the handle and blade tip.

00:13:17.990 --> 00:13:21.010
And there's some
pretty bitchin' carving

00:13:21.010 --> 00:13:23.270
going on in that paddle.

00:13:23.270 --> 00:13:25.200
Paddles are really
fun to make, actually.

00:13:25.200 --> 00:13:26.866
And if you want to
get into woodworking,

00:13:26.866 --> 00:13:31.170
I recommend a paddle
because it only

00:13:31.170 --> 00:13:36.260
takes one piece of wood
and some hand tools.

00:13:36.260 --> 00:13:40.260
It's a great introduction
to hand tools.

00:13:40.260 --> 00:13:48.970
Moving onto my prepared
remarks, the first little piece

00:13:48.970 --> 00:13:54.040
is a quick anecdote about a
waiting room not far from here.

00:13:54.040 --> 00:13:55.410
It's in Santa Monica.

00:13:55.410 --> 00:13:58.990
And, gosh, I guess it
was about 15 years ago.

00:13:58.990 --> 00:14:06.710
I was just out of high school,
and I was auditioning--

00:14:06.710 --> 00:14:11.210
I was new in town-- when you're
trying to get arrested here,

00:14:11.210 --> 00:14:16.020
you try and get kick-ass
jobs and auditions,

00:14:16.020 --> 00:14:18.750
but you also go to
commercial auditions.

00:14:18.750 --> 00:14:20.850
You go to any bullshit
that will pay you

00:14:20.850 --> 00:14:24.410
$1, because you're broke.

00:14:24.410 --> 00:14:27.315
So I was going to all
these commercial auditions.

00:14:30.450 --> 00:14:33.690
If you guys know anybody that
are good with the internet

00:14:33.690 --> 00:14:37.730
and stuff-- I've
never seen this again,

00:14:37.730 --> 00:14:40.140
but there's a commercial
that I did for a steakhouse.

00:14:43.092 --> 00:14:44.050
The fuck was it called?

00:14:44.050 --> 00:14:45.175
It was in the southeast.

00:14:45.175 --> 00:14:49.210
I don't remember the name of
the steakhouse, and I won't.

00:14:52.010 --> 00:14:53.620
So I did a couple
commercial spots.

00:14:53.620 --> 00:14:56.290
If you can find that, it would
probably be funny to look at.

00:14:56.290 --> 00:14:59.530
I escaped from jail.

00:14:59.530 --> 00:15:02.910
And I was conflicted
going to these auditions.

00:15:02.910 --> 00:15:04.990
I'm a classically
trained theater actor.

00:15:04.990 --> 00:15:08.630
At the time, I was incredibly
snotty about myself.

00:15:08.630 --> 00:15:12.000
I performed works
of theater, like, I

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:14.270
memorized two
hours of literature

00:15:14.270 --> 00:15:16.780
and then presented
dramatically on stage.

00:15:16.780 --> 00:15:19.910
And then you're
sitting in a room

00:15:19.910 --> 00:15:22.140
with a bunch of guys
that are like, all right.

00:15:22.140 --> 00:15:24.340
You chew a piece of
gum and it tastes bad,

00:15:24.340 --> 00:15:25.774
so you make a funny face.

00:15:25.774 --> 00:15:26.565
And that's the job.

00:15:26.565 --> 00:15:31.350
And you're just like-- Jesus
Christ, this is demoralizing.

00:15:31.350 --> 00:15:33.900
So I had been in
town for about a

00:15:33.900 --> 00:15:37.030
year when I found myself
auditioning for a Budweiser

00:15:37.030 --> 00:15:38.320
spot.

00:15:38.320 --> 00:15:40.360
I hauled my ass out
to Santa Monica.

00:15:40.360 --> 00:15:43.600
Same old waiting room,
full of maybe 60 guys.

00:15:43.600 --> 00:15:46.660
It's a big square room, and
each wall has a bench along it,

00:15:46.660 --> 00:15:48.680
so it's a big square of guys.

00:15:48.680 --> 00:15:54.540
Mostly beer-loving, baseball
fan-looking guys, so fat guys.

00:15:54.540 --> 00:15:58.180
The schtick was, you're
in the bleachers,

00:15:58.180 --> 00:15:59.840
holding at a baseball game.

00:15:59.840 --> 00:16:04.230
And you hear the sound of a
home run crack off the bat.

00:16:04.230 --> 00:16:08.967
The crowd noise builds, and
you're holding two huge beers.

00:16:08.967 --> 00:16:10.550
You probably remember
this commercial.

00:16:10.550 --> 00:16:12.720
And you don't want to
set either one down

00:16:12.720 --> 00:16:15.680
because Budweiser
is so delicious,

00:16:15.680 --> 00:16:18.480
or because ballpark
beers are so expensive.

00:16:18.480 --> 00:16:21.600
So you want to track this whole
thing until the home run hits

00:16:21.600 --> 00:16:23.250
you on the forehead, of course.

00:16:23.250 --> 00:16:26.190
And you make a hilarious
face, and then you fall over.

00:16:26.190 --> 00:16:29.260
So the salient question was,
who makes the funny face

00:16:29.260 --> 00:16:33.120
of getting hit on the head
with a home run ball the best?

00:16:33.120 --> 00:16:35.340
The Bud spot also
contained the role

00:16:35.340 --> 00:16:37.760
of a little old peanut
vendor, so there

00:16:37.760 --> 00:16:41.020
was a motley throng of
hedonist looking guys,

00:16:41.020 --> 00:16:43.180
the beer drinkers,
together with a bunch

00:16:43.180 --> 00:16:45.130
of assorted little old men.

00:16:45.130 --> 00:16:49.740
I was looking around, silently
calculating the carpenter wages

00:16:49.740 --> 00:16:52.460
I was not earning,
and I realized

00:16:52.460 --> 00:16:56.330
that sitting next to me was
Donald Gibb, the guy who

00:16:56.330 --> 00:16:59.390
played Ogre in
"Revenge of the Nerds."

00:16:59.390 --> 00:17:01.930
I was the appropriate age
for "Revenge of the Nerds"

00:17:01.930 --> 00:17:04.950
to have been a hugely
beloved movie for me.

00:17:04.950 --> 00:17:07.054
My wife passed on that
movie, by the way,

00:17:07.054 --> 00:17:08.720
which, something we've
had to work past.

00:17:11.460 --> 00:17:14.609
But it was a seminal film.

00:17:14.609 --> 00:17:18.810
I was the right audience
for "Revenge of the Nerds."

00:17:18.810 --> 00:17:19.480
A classic.

00:17:19.480 --> 00:17:22.849
He was also in the movie "Blood
Sport," for mercy's sake.

00:17:22.849 --> 00:17:26.500
This guy-- I remember
this guy, "Nerds!"

00:17:26.500 --> 00:17:29.450
He was a hero to me and every
other teenager in the '80s,

00:17:29.450 --> 00:17:32.430
and now he's sitting next to
me at this commercial audition?

00:17:32.430 --> 00:17:33.410
I thought, good God.

00:17:33.410 --> 00:17:37.510
You can be this minor movie
star and do a ton of TV roles,

00:17:37.510 --> 00:17:39.760
and then 10 years later
you're sitting next to me

00:17:39.760 --> 00:17:42.270
at a fucking Budweiser spot.

00:17:42.270 --> 00:17:43.650
I was truly reeling.

00:17:43.650 --> 00:17:46.960
So I got up and walked around
the room to clear my head.

00:17:46.960 --> 00:17:48.960
Across the room, I
passed another guy

00:17:48.960 --> 00:17:50.300
whose face rang a bell.

00:17:50.300 --> 00:17:52.920
And I looked back,
and I'll be goddamned

00:17:52.920 --> 00:17:57.940
if it wasn't fucking Carmine
from "Laverne and Shirley."

00:17:57.940 --> 00:18:00.680
I surreptitiously looked at
the head shot in his hand.

00:18:00.680 --> 00:18:05.140
And at the bottom, sure enough,
it read, Eddie "Carmine" Mecca.

00:18:05.140 --> 00:18:08.302
I was dumbstruck, thinking,
you've got to be kidding me.

00:18:08.302 --> 00:18:10.010
It might as well have
been John Schneider

00:18:10.010 --> 00:18:12.200
from "The Dukes of
Hazzard," or Burt Reynolds.

00:18:12.200 --> 00:18:14.630
You can be fucking
Carmine and now you're

00:18:14.630 --> 00:18:16.530
at this Budweiser spot?

00:18:16.530 --> 00:18:19.030
Just then, Carmine
started up a conversation

00:18:19.030 --> 00:18:21.010
with the little old
man next to him.

00:18:21.010 --> 00:18:22.480
"Hey, you're Joey such and such.

00:18:22.480 --> 00:18:25.270
You were in "Guys and Dolls"
and "Singing in the Rain."

00:18:25.270 --> 00:18:27.470
Joey was apparently
an old song and dance

00:18:27.470 --> 00:18:30.230
man, with whom Carmine
was very impressed.

00:18:30.230 --> 00:18:32.775
In a grinning reply, the man
said, "Ah, come on, Eddie.

00:18:32.775 --> 00:18:33.710
You saw that shit?

00:18:33.710 --> 00:18:35.666
Fuhgettaboutit."

00:18:35.666 --> 00:18:40.000
Fate, that fickle
bitch, was grabbing

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:42.670
me oh so firmly
by the shorthairs

00:18:42.670 --> 00:18:45.010
and sending me a
very clear message.

00:18:45.010 --> 00:18:47.700
I ran out to the payphone,
called my commercial agent,

00:18:47.700 --> 00:18:50.400
and said, thank you kindly but
I'm not doing this anymore.

00:18:50.400 --> 00:18:52.880
This is not the life for me.

00:18:52.880 --> 00:18:55.300
There was no shame in
these commercial auditions.

00:18:55.300 --> 00:18:59.340
I just knew that I would rather
be making a solid $20 an hour

00:18:59.340 --> 00:19:01.970
than making zero money to
sit and wait for a lottery

00:19:01.970 --> 00:19:04.480
ticket that could pay off big.

00:19:04.480 --> 00:19:09.100
I understood in that
moment what Robert Mitchum

00:19:09.100 --> 00:19:13.660
had meant when he said,
"Acting is no job for a man."

00:19:13.660 --> 00:19:16.440
Years later, I got to
work with Eddie "Carmine"

00:19:16.440 --> 00:19:19.390
Mecca on an episode of
Children's Hospital.

00:19:19.390 --> 00:19:21.680
And he was a dreamboat.

00:19:21.680 --> 00:19:25.430
Between takes, he would sing
standards and Sinatra tunes.

00:19:25.430 --> 00:19:27.180
He was a total peach.

00:19:27.180 --> 00:19:29.680
Now if I could only shake
hands with the Ogre,

00:19:29.680 --> 00:19:34.412
I could bring my Budweiser
trauma to a neat resolution.

00:19:34.412 --> 00:19:39.172
[APPLAUSE]

00:19:39.172 --> 00:19:42.030
You're very generous.

00:19:42.030 --> 00:19:44.690
Thank you.

00:19:44.690 --> 00:19:48.730
I'll give you one more little
piece, subtly entitled,

00:19:48.730 --> 00:19:54.770
"Don't Be an Asshole," I find
it consistently difficult

00:19:54.770 --> 00:19:59.030
to get around the notion that
we are all, in our very natures,

00:19:59.030 --> 00:20:00.230
assholes.

00:20:00.230 --> 00:20:01.670
I'm an asshole.

00:20:01.670 --> 00:20:04.870
I'm afraid you are also.

00:20:04.870 --> 00:20:07.270
That's why the conversation
about good manners

00:20:07.270 --> 00:20:09.510
even exists in the first place.

00:20:09.510 --> 00:20:13.530
We're cognizant, curious
beings, capable of philosophical

00:20:13.530 --> 00:20:17.170
thought-- nuclear physics,
repeating Nerf weaponry,

00:20:17.170 --> 00:20:20.250
global consciousness,
Glade air fresheners,

00:20:20.250 --> 00:20:22.730
and sentient automobiles.

00:20:22.730 --> 00:20:24.990
But we're assholes first.

00:20:24.990 --> 00:20:26.600
But this is because
before we can

00:20:26.600 --> 00:20:29.970
begin to argue mortgage
rates and tuition hikes,

00:20:29.970 --> 00:20:31.540
before we can roll
up our sleeves

00:20:31.540 --> 00:20:35.360
and thread a profusion catheter
into the cholesterol-choked

00:20:35.360 --> 00:20:39.640
artery of today's society,
we-- every one of us--

00:20:39.640 --> 00:20:42.830
must first replenish our
mammalian bodies with food

00:20:42.830 --> 00:20:45.440
and water, while
establishing and maintaining

00:20:45.440 --> 00:20:47.930
a comfortable climate
around our bodies

00:20:47.930 --> 00:20:50.260
through the employment of
garments and heating/cooling

00:20:50.260 --> 00:20:52.070
cooling systems.

00:20:52.070 --> 00:20:53.820
Before we can
arrive at the office

00:20:53.820 --> 00:20:56.250
to resume our efforts
to improve, say,

00:20:56.250 --> 00:20:58.750
worldwide Muslim-Christian
relations,

00:20:58.750 --> 00:21:01.860
or the infrastructure of the
Haitian public utility system,

00:21:01.860 --> 00:21:05.950
we must commune-- and more
