00:33:56.245 --> 00:34:00.860
NICK OFFERMAN: Well,
that's a good question.

00:34:00.860 --> 00:34:04.520
I generally give
them seven strikes.

00:34:04.520 --> 00:34:09.040
No, I mean I grew up in a very
conservative, white, small town

00:34:09.040 --> 00:34:13.739
where I met one
black person once.

00:34:13.739 --> 00:34:17.280
And I had heard of Jews,
but like I got to college

00:34:17.280 --> 00:34:21.860
and a kid was getting hazed and
he had lox in his underwear.

00:34:21.860 --> 00:34:23.290
And I said, what is lox?

00:34:23.290 --> 00:34:25.060
And he looked at me funny.

00:34:25.060 --> 00:34:26.710
And I said sorry, what is lox?

00:34:26.710 --> 00:34:28.449
And he said, salmon.

00:34:28.449 --> 00:34:29.105
Lox and bagels.

00:34:29.105 --> 00:34:30.230
And I said, what's a bagel?

00:34:33.840 --> 00:34:35.244
And I said, oh are you serious?

00:34:35.244 --> 00:34:36.295
Like there's still Jews?

00:34:39.389 --> 00:34:44.449
I had heard about
them in Sunday school.

00:34:44.449 --> 00:34:50.600
My town was that white and
sort of Catholic and Methodist.

00:34:50.600 --> 00:34:58.250
And so I mean, my solution was
to move to an urban area, where

00:34:58.250 --> 00:35:00.625
I could find people
that were cool.

00:35:03.830 --> 00:35:06.690
But I've had lots of
conversations with people

00:35:06.690 --> 00:35:09.310
in my family, or old
friends from home

00:35:09.310 --> 00:35:11.410
where you do what you can.

00:35:11.410 --> 00:35:16.280
I mean, either you
eschew their company

00:35:16.280 --> 00:35:21.200
or in the case of family
members, I try to gently say,

00:35:21.200 --> 00:35:23.890
I know that, like, you feel that
way because of this or that.

00:35:23.890 --> 00:35:27.930
Or, you I know that racism
was very prevalent in,

00:35:27.930 --> 00:35:30.510
like, your generation or in
your parents' generation.

00:35:30.510 --> 00:35:36.440
But some stuff went down
in, like, the '50s and '60s

00:35:36.440 --> 00:35:38.080
that you might
want to check out.

00:35:38.080 --> 00:35:40.480
There was this dude, Martin
Luther King, Jr. Like,

00:35:40.480 --> 00:35:42.050
there's some
exposition you might

00:35:42.050 --> 00:35:45.320
want to avail yourself of.

00:35:45.320 --> 00:35:47.990
But I remember having a talk
with a member of my family.

00:35:47.990 --> 00:35:50.910
I took them to see the
movie "American Beauty."

00:35:50.910 --> 00:35:54.429
And it was a very pointed
trip to the movies.

00:35:54.429 --> 00:35:55.970
I didn't tell them
anything about it.

00:35:55.970 --> 00:35:56.845
And we saw the movie.

00:35:56.845 --> 00:35:58.690
And then we got out
and I said, so what

00:35:58.690 --> 00:36:00.540
do you think about that?

00:36:00.540 --> 00:36:03.680
And he said, well, no,
I'm OK with those guys,

00:36:03.680 --> 00:36:06.680
as long as they don't
try to hold my hand.

00:36:06.680 --> 00:36:10.270
And I said, that's why I
wanted to take you to this.

00:36:10.270 --> 00:36:12.330
Like, that's like
a fear-- that's

00:36:12.330 --> 00:36:16.570
an old-school fear that you
have been instilled with.

00:36:16.570 --> 00:36:20.190
And can you understand
that that's bad,

00:36:20.190 --> 00:36:23.370
that if some people felt that
way about you because you're

00:36:23.370 --> 00:36:27.250
white or you're brunette,
or because you're straight?

00:36:27.250 --> 00:36:30.540
Can you understand that
that's discriminatory?

00:36:30.540 --> 00:36:37.500
And in my world of
theater and artists,

00:36:37.500 --> 00:36:39.760
it's an incredible melting pot.

00:36:39.760 --> 00:36:46.000
It's a veritable Benetton
ad of races and sexualities,

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:47.500
and they're all
people that I love.

00:36:47.500 --> 00:36:48.458
And we're all the same.

00:36:48.458 --> 00:36:51.930
We're all working together
to make something.

00:36:51.930 --> 00:36:55.180
And many of my friends
that you've met

00:36:55.180 --> 00:36:59.470
are wonderful people
that you like.

00:36:59.470 --> 00:37:01.490
And can you understand
how you need

00:37:01.490 --> 00:37:05.370
to see them as human beings,
rather than some sort of group?

00:37:05.370 --> 00:37:08.150
So I try to have gentle
conversations about it.

00:37:08.150 --> 00:37:12.240
And sometimes I think
it's a game that's

00:37:12.240 --> 00:37:15.990
won by inches, certainly
not by slam-dunks.

00:37:15.990 --> 00:37:17.542
Remain patient.

00:37:17.542 --> 00:37:18.250
That's the thing.

00:37:18.250 --> 00:37:21.940
That's what that chapter is
about is like, I can never

00:37:21.940 --> 00:37:26.640
lose sight of the fact that we
all have it in us to be like,

00:37:26.640 --> 00:37:27.320
goddammit.

00:37:27.320 --> 00:37:30.330
That Honda cut me
off in traffic.

00:37:30.330 --> 00:37:30.830
Fuck Hondas!

00:37:30.830 --> 00:37:31.809
No, no.

00:37:31.809 --> 00:37:32.309
No.

00:37:32.309 --> 00:37:32.809
No.

00:37:32.809 --> 00:37:33.790
No.

00:37:33.790 --> 00:37:34.480
It's not Hondas.

00:37:34.480 --> 00:37:39.320
And we have to remind
ourselves to mind our manners,

00:37:39.320 --> 00:37:42.456
and open the door
for one another.

00:37:42.456 --> 00:37:43.350
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:37:43.350 --> 00:37:44.308
NICK OFFERMAN: You bet.

00:37:50.070 --> 00:37:53.620
AUDIENCE: So I think you and
Tom Selleck probably have, like,

00:37:53.620 --> 00:37:55.480
the greatest moustaches
in Hollywood.

00:37:55.480 --> 00:37:56.995
NICK OFFERMAN:
That's very generous.

00:37:56.995 --> 00:37:58.710
AUDIENCE: So I mean,
how old were you

00:37:58.710 --> 00:38:00.960
when you first grew it out,
and at what point were you

00:38:00.960 --> 00:38:03.616
like, I got something here?

00:38:03.616 --> 00:38:08.560
NICK OFFERMAN: Well, when I
was at theater school at age

00:38:08.560 --> 00:38:13.280
like 18 or 19, and
it was interesting.

00:38:13.280 --> 00:38:16.880
I was very much a
greenhorn, like fresh kid

00:38:16.880 --> 00:38:18.960
from the corn fields.

00:38:18.960 --> 00:38:21.010
And I sort of saw
the lay of the land.

00:38:21.010 --> 00:38:27.320
And I saw, even in the microcosm
of my theater conservatory

00:38:27.320 --> 00:38:30.510
in Champaign-Urbana,
I saw the sort

00:38:30.510 --> 00:38:32.110
of different genres of actor.

00:38:32.110 --> 00:38:36.340
There were cute people,
there were funny people,

00:38:36.340 --> 00:38:40.750
there were some that had both,
that I was very envious of.

00:38:40.750 --> 00:38:44.740
But I quickly determined that,
of the options available to me,

00:38:44.740 --> 00:38:47.500
I wanted to be a
character actor.

00:38:47.500 --> 00:38:52.560
I didn't want to go try and
achieve the route of someone

00:38:52.560 --> 00:38:55.120
looking the same all
the time, and playing

00:38:55.120 --> 00:38:59.350
the same version of some sort
of heroic guy, or something.

00:38:59.350 --> 00:39:02.980
And so I immediately
began to capitalize

00:39:02.980 --> 00:39:04.970
on my hair and my facial hair.

00:39:04.970 --> 00:39:10.420
And sort of used every tool
in the follicular toolbox.

00:39:13.370 --> 00:39:16.690
And so I was so excited to
get out of my little town,

00:39:16.690 --> 00:39:20.020
and finally be able to do
things that I saw in the movie

00:39:20.020 --> 00:39:22.220
"Hair," like grow
kick-ass mutton

00:39:22.220 --> 00:39:24.840
chops like our last questioner.

00:39:24.840 --> 00:39:29.510
And I'd say it was
probably in my early 20s

00:39:29.510 --> 00:39:34.830
when my man's mustache
fully was achieved.

00:39:34.830 --> 00:39:37.230
And it was clearly--
I was like, oh that's

00:39:37.230 --> 00:39:42.170
going to be a great-- of my
12 different looks, that's

00:39:42.170 --> 00:39:43.490
going to be a good one.

00:39:43.490 --> 00:39:47.090
I hope I can play
a sheriff someday.

00:39:47.090 --> 00:39:48.422
But I come by it honest.

00:39:48.422 --> 00:39:50.630
Like, people often ask me
for tips on how to grow it.

00:39:50.630 --> 00:39:51.910
And I say, don't shave.

00:39:54.840 --> 00:39:57.045
If you don't do anything,
it just-- it appears.

00:39:57.045 --> 00:39:58.110
AUDIENCE: Usually
how it happens.

00:39:58.110 --> 00:39:58.410
Cool.

00:39:58.410 --> 00:39:59.470
NICK OFFERMAN: Thank you.

00:39:59.470 --> 00:40:00.960
INTERVIEWER: It's one o'clock.

00:40:00.960 --> 00:40:02.585
Is it time for one
quick last question?

00:40:02.585 --> 00:40:06.060
NICK OFFERMAN: Yeah,
I got 15 more minutes.

00:40:06.060 --> 00:40:08.060
INTERVIEWER: I was going
to say, so your current

00:40:08.060 --> 00:40:09.643
mustache that you
have right now, this

00:40:09.643 --> 00:40:11.675
is the shooting mustache, right?

00:40:11.675 --> 00:40:12.550
NICK OFFERMAN: It is.

00:40:12.550 --> 00:40:14.990
This is the A game.

00:40:18.455 --> 00:40:19.240
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:40:19.240 --> 00:40:20.200
NICK OFFERMAN: Hello.

00:40:20.200 --> 00:40:23.969
AUDIENCE: I have a really
big crush on Ron Swanson.

00:40:23.969 --> 00:40:25.010
NICK OFFERMAN: I'm sorry.

00:40:25.010 --> 00:40:26.820
Oh, so you have a really
big crush on Ron Swanson?

00:40:26.820 --> 00:40:27.403
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:40:27.403 --> 00:40:31.020
How much of you is
in the Ron character?

00:40:35.690 --> 00:40:37.612
NICK OFFERMAN: Not
very much, apparently.

00:40:40.324 --> 00:40:42.690
AUDIENCE: No, like
the breakfast eating,

00:40:42.690 --> 00:40:45.369
the scotch, the steak
the libertarian--

00:40:45.369 --> 00:40:46.910
NICK OFFERMAN: To
be fair, many of us

00:40:46.910 --> 00:40:54.360
eat breakfast and consume
meat entrees and whiskey.

00:40:54.360 --> 00:40:58.524
AUDIENCE: There are lots of
vegans and vegetarians here.

00:40:58.524 --> 00:41:01.060
NICK OFFERMAN: I'm
actually down with that.

00:41:01.060 --> 00:41:03.710
I applaud healthy
eating choices.

00:41:03.710 --> 00:41:10.070
So as you can see, I'm nothing
like Ron Swanson, ma'am.

00:41:10.070 --> 00:41:14.030
AUDIENCE: I have a
little crush on you, too.

00:41:14.030 --> 00:41:15.309
A two-parter.

00:41:15.309 --> 00:41:17.100
What's the character
you most want to play?

00:41:17.100 --> 00:41:19.141
NICK OFFERMAN: The character
I most want to play.

00:41:21.780 --> 00:41:23.360
It's a good question.

00:41:23.360 --> 00:41:24.955
I'm too old to play Hamlet.

00:41:28.310 --> 00:41:29.970
Please, don't argue with me.

00:41:33.180 --> 00:41:34.740
I passed it, like,
three months ago.

00:41:37.410 --> 00:41:38.050
I don't know.

00:41:38.050 --> 00:41:41.830
I don't have a dream
character as much

00:41:41.830 --> 00:41:47.210
as I just love to
perform great writing.

00:41:47.210 --> 00:41:49.170
And so, if I was to
sit here and say,

00:41:49.170 --> 00:41:53.040
I wanted to play-- there's
a great comic book called

00:41:53.040 --> 00:42:00.107
"The Boys," and the head of
this gang is a part I love.

00:42:00.107 --> 00:42:01.440
There's lots of parts like that.

00:42:01.440 --> 00:42:04.414
But until somebody
turns in a script where

00:42:04.414 --> 00:42:06.330
I'm like, oh, this is
great-- I want to do it,

00:42:06.330 --> 00:42:10.340
it's good writing that moves me
much more than the notion of,

00:42:10.340 --> 00:42:12.700
I would love to play
James K. Polk someday.

00:42:15.360 --> 00:42:17.420
Wait a second.

00:42:17.420 --> 00:42:18.640
The Napoleon of the South.

00:42:18.640 --> 00:42:21.560
That's not a bad idea.

00:42:21.560 --> 00:42:26.430
I mean also, being handed this
crazy dream role of a lifetime,

00:42:26.430 --> 00:42:31.400
it's hard at the moment
to care about-- nothing.

00:42:31.400 --> 00:42:37.470
I don't want to play any parts,
because this is such a feast

00:42:37.470 --> 00:42:41.560
that I feel like I don't
need to eat for a while.

00:42:41.560 --> 00:42:42.290
But we'll see.

00:42:45.200 --> 00:42:53.280
I'd love to play a fop,
some sort of mincing fop.

00:42:53.280 --> 00:42:54.510
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:42:54.510 --> 00:42:55.635
NICK OFFERMAN: My pleasure.

00:42:55.635 --> 00:42:57.180
INTERVIEWER: So it's
kind of interesting

00:42:57.180 --> 00:42:59.388
that you've become so
identified with this character.

00:42:59.388 --> 00:43:02.890
But I learned from the book that
you actually went into audition

00:43:02.890 --> 00:43:04.940
for a different
role on the show.

00:43:04.940 --> 00:43:06.930
Why do you think this
ended up being the one

00:43:06.930 --> 00:43:07.902
that you were cast in?

00:43:07.902 --> 00:43:09.360
NICK OFFERMAN:
Well, in a nutshell,

00:43:09.360 --> 00:43:12.870
you can get all
the juicy details

00:43:12.870 --> 00:43:15.412
Chapter [INTENTIONALLY
MUMBLES] in the book.

00:43:20.600 --> 00:43:23.150
Mike Schur and Greg
Daniels were creating

00:43:23.150 --> 00:43:25.780
the show very organically.

00:43:25.780 --> 00:43:29.890
They knew some sort of
archetypes they wanted.

00:43:29.890 --> 00:43:33.550
They knew they had Amy and
Aziz and Aubrey, I think.

00:43:33.550 --> 00:43:39.135
And they thought, I
think we want Rashida.

00:43:39.135 --> 00:43:41.760
And so they were coming up with,
they were filling in like, OK,

00:43:41.760 --> 00:43:45.220
we need a guy who maybe
gets involved with Rashida--

00:43:45.220 --> 00:43:47.590
were filling out the cast.

00:43:47.590 --> 00:43:53.990
And so they had me in to
read for that guy, and also

00:43:53.990 --> 00:43:56.350
Adam Scott, the day I went in.

00:43:56.350 --> 00:43:58.280
And I've known Adam
for a long time,

00:43:58.280 --> 00:44:02.170
and he's such a
funny, great guy.

00:44:02.170 --> 00:44:04.550
He's also just
such a great actor,

00:44:04.550 --> 00:44:07.000
that there's no one I
could think of that I would

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:10.480
rather not fucking
see at an audition

00:44:10.480 --> 00:44:13.070
where I'm like, oh great.

00:44:13.070 --> 00:44:16.240
Which one of us-- I want
to see you kiss Rashida,

00:44:16.240 --> 00:44:18.860
or I see myself.

00:44:18.860 --> 00:44:23.240
But so we both went in
that day, and neither of us

00:44:23.240 --> 00:44:23.990
ended up doing it.

00:44:26.710 --> 00:44:29.930
I think it's experimental,
where they say OK,

00:44:29.930 --> 00:44:32.975
maybe that guy is too husky.

00:44:36.200 --> 00:44:37.669
Maybe he's too goddamn charming.

00:44:37.669 --> 00:44:39.335
Nobody would believe
that he was single.

00:44:42.370 --> 00:44:47.060
Or whatever, and they then
further shaped the characters.

00:44:47.060 --> 00:44:50.820
And NBC had a say,
where they said--

00:44:50.820 --> 00:44:54.020
and this is a funny quote that I
heard from somebody, where they

00:44:54.020 --> 00:44:56.940
came back and said, we
asked you for Aaron Eckhart.

00:44:56.940 --> 00:44:59.760
And you brought
us Nick Offerman,

00:44:59.760 --> 00:45:02.425
with indignant,
righteous indignation.

00:45:07.550 --> 00:45:09.420
I thought I was in
the Eckhart file,

00:45:09.420 --> 00:45:13.050
but I guess it's not the case.

00:45:13.050 --> 00:45:16.560
So thankfully, they really
wanted me on the show.

00:45:16.560 --> 00:45:20.730
And they had conceived
of this boss character.

00:45:20.730 --> 00:45:23.282
I think they had initially
pictured him as being older,

00:45:23.282 --> 00:45:24.990
you know, being more
of an administrator,

00:45:24.990 --> 00:45:28.110
like a high school principal.

00:45:28.110 --> 00:45:31.330
And so that's why it took a
long time to convince NBC.

00:45:31.330 --> 00:45:32.795
So they said OK,
you don't want him

00:45:32.795 --> 00:45:35.160
as somebody who kisses anybody.

00:45:35.160 --> 00:45:36.420
We think he's funny.

00:45:36.420 --> 00:45:37.980
Can we put him in
this other part?

00:45:37.980 --> 00:45:38.938
And they were like, no.

00:45:38.938 --> 00:45:41.240
That needs to be a
guy with white hair.

00:45:41.240 --> 00:45:44.650
And so eventually,
they came around.

00:45:44.650 --> 00:45:47.720
And I'm so eternally
grateful to those guys,

00:45:47.720 --> 00:45:53.350
because it's really hard,
as you all are well aware.

00:45:53.350 --> 00:45:56.830
When you're dealing
on a corporate level

00:45:56.830 --> 00:46:01.170
with an artistic project, it's
really hard for the corporation

00:46:01.170 --> 00:46:03.300
to keep their fingers
out of your pudding.

00:46:03.300 --> 00:46:05.920
And if they've hired
you to paint a picture,

00:46:05.920 --> 00:46:09.230
there's somebody that wants to
stand there and suggest a brush

00:46:09.230 --> 00:46:11.483
to say, what if
you do red there?

00:46:11.483 --> 00:46:15.190
OK, sorry-- and try to tell
you how to paint your picture.

00:46:15.190 --> 00:46:18.370
And so I'm so grateful to
Mike Scher and Greg Daniels

00:46:18.370 --> 00:46:22.080
for sticking to their
guns over a long process

00:46:22.080 --> 00:46:25.000
to give me this part,
because-- and of course,

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:28.760
you know, then once it
works, then the corporation

00:46:28.760 --> 00:46:30.780
is like, we found this guy.

00:46:30.780 --> 00:46:32.900
He's terrific.

00:46:32.900 --> 00:46:36.327
It took some doing, but
we got him in the part.

00:46:36.327 --> 00:46:38.410
INTERVIEWER: All right,
I'll take another question

00:46:38.410 --> 00:46:39.656
from the audience?

00:46:39.656 --> 00:46:41.620
AUDIENCE: Coming from
conservatory training,

00:46:41.620 --> 00:46:43.620
it sounds like maybe
you're more classical,

00:46:43.620 --> 00:46:45.530
or were not always
considering comedy.

00:46:45.530 --> 00:46:47.380
Who were your comedy
influences growing up?

00:46:47.380 --> 00:46:50.412
Was it, like, Newhart,
Don Rickles, or--

00:46:50.412 --> 00:46:53.260
NICK OFFERMAN: No.

00:46:53.260 --> 00:46:55.300
I'm a fan.

00:46:55.300 --> 00:46:56.610
I'm a fan.

00:46:56.610 --> 00:46:59.800
Newhart-- it would be
more of an influence.

00:46:59.800 --> 00:47:01.450
I'm not super
familiar with Rickles,

00:47:01.450 --> 00:47:05.370
although I think he's super
funny, what I've seen.

00:47:05.370 --> 00:47:08.370
But it's a weird thing
in show business.

00:47:08.370 --> 00:47:10.320
It took me a long time
to learn that they

00:47:10.320 --> 00:47:13.510
want you to be a specialist.

00:47:13.510 --> 00:47:17.880
In theater, you do-- in any
given season at a theater,

00:47:17.880 --> 00:47:21.210
you might do a Sam Sheppard
play, a Shakespeare, a Martin

00:47:21.210 --> 00:47:24.950
McDonagh play, some
weird experimental thing.

00:47:24.950 --> 00:47:27.850
You might do the
broadest "Phaedo" farce--

00:47:27.850 --> 00:47:30.430
hilarious, like,
door slamming comedy.

00:47:30.430 --> 00:47:34.550
And then you may do the most
serious Chekhovian drama.

00:47:34.550 --> 00:47:37.130
And you're equipped,
hopefully, with the tools

00:47:37.130 --> 00:47:38.680
to do all of those things.

00:47:38.680 --> 00:47:41.990
And they're all enjoyable
in their own way.

00:47:41.990 --> 00:47:44.310
I always loved comedy.

00:47:44.310 --> 00:47:49.260
As a kid out in the country,
the movies of Mel Brooks

00:47:49.260 --> 00:47:52.500
were incredibly
influential for me.

00:47:52.500 --> 00:47:55.730
Steve Martin, early SNL.

00:47:55.730 --> 00:47:58.520
I sat in school, I
remember in grade school

00:47:58.520 --> 00:48:01.990
sitting there doing
pushups with my eyebrows,

00:48:01.990 --> 00:48:05.270
because I wanted to be John
Belushi when I grew up.

00:48:05.270 --> 00:48:07.280
He was a very big hero to me.

00:48:07.280 --> 00:48:11.660
And now I can do the
wave with my eyebrows.

00:48:11.660 --> 00:48:12.620
Thank you, thanks.

00:48:16.070 --> 00:48:18.350
But I was literally
in my mid 30s

00:48:18.350 --> 00:48:20.690
when I realized--
I had been in town,

00:48:20.690 --> 00:48:22.960
I had been working
here and there,

00:48:22.960 --> 00:48:26.400
and slowly getting
better and better work.

00:48:26.400 --> 00:48:27.700
But then something was weird.

00:48:27.700 --> 00:48:30.220
There was a certain
genre of like,

00:48:30.220 --> 00:48:32.390
a Will Ferrell or
a Jim Carrey movie,

00:48:32.390 --> 00:48:34.410
or these big comedies
where maybe there

00:48:34.410 --> 00:48:36.050
would be 10 firemen.

00:48:36.050 --> 00:48:38.270
And I'd see the
movie and say, there

00:48:38.270 --> 00:48:41.360
wasn't a-- I couldn't
read for Fireman Number 7?

00:48:41.360 --> 00:48:43.300
Like, what's the deal?

00:48:43.300 --> 00:48:46.500
And I had learned that the
people casting these movies

00:48:46.500 --> 00:48:50.280
have these lists of, these
are the people that do comedy.

00:48:50.280 --> 00:48:52.160
These are the people
that play tennis.

00:48:52.160 --> 00:48:54.270
These are the people
that speak French.

00:48:54.270 --> 00:48:58.810
And I literally had to make
a concerted effort to go--

00:48:58.810 --> 00:49:03.040
and the people that do comedy
come from the Upright Citizens

00:49:03.040 --> 00:49:05.740
Brigade, Second
City, Groundlings--

00:49:05.740 --> 00:49:11.380
all of these venerated comedy
schools, where people learn

00:49:11.380 --> 00:49:14.046
improv and sketch, or stand-up.

00:49:14.046 --> 00:49:15.670
Those are the people
that are allowed--

00:49:15.670 --> 00:49:18.800
that are licensed
to perform comedy.

00:49:18.800 --> 00:49:21.890
And when I started
getting work in comedy,

00:49:21.890 --> 00:49:23.810
some of the more
substantial stuff

00:49:23.810 --> 00:49:26.740
was I did a bunch of
the George Lopez show.

00:49:26.740 --> 00:49:29.840
And a couple casting directors
after that would say to me,

00:49:29.840 --> 00:49:31.640
oh, I didn't know you do comedy!

00:49:31.640 --> 00:49:34.480
As though I was
knitting, or something.

00:49:34.480 --> 00:49:38.370
Oh, I didn't know
that you crochet!

00:49:38.370 --> 00:49:42.350
And so I made a
concerted effort.

00:49:42.350 --> 00:49:43.980
I called Amy, who I had known.

00:49:43.980 --> 00:49:45.230
Amy Poehler.

00:49:45.230 --> 00:49:47.820
I'd known her in Chicago
just from palling around

00:49:47.820 --> 00:49:48.700
in the early 90s.

00:49:48.700 --> 00:49:52.150
We never saw each other's--
it's two separate worlds,

00:49:52.150 --> 00:49:54.390
The world of comedy, and
then the world of, like,

00:49:54.390 --> 00:49:57.020
legit theater--
Steppenwolf Theater.

00:49:57.020 --> 00:50:01.190
In town, it would be like the
Taper and the Geffen, South

00:50:01.190 --> 00:50:07.550
Coast Rep versus Groundlings and
Second City and Improv Olympic.

00:50:07.550 --> 00:50:11.370
So we were buddies,
but we never went

00:50:11.370 --> 00:50:12.680
to where each other worked.

00:50:12.680 --> 00:50:14.180
It was like, how's
your thing going?

00:50:14.180 --> 00:50:16.980
You make up shit in
front of people in bars?

00:50:16.980 --> 00:50:18.720
Have fun.

00:50:18.720 --> 00:50:19.410
I'm doing Ibsen.

00:50:19.410 --> 00:50:21.690
I'm doing a little Brecht piece.

00:50:21.690 --> 00:50:24.270
No big deal.

00:50:24.270 --> 00:50:26.224
Good luck.

00:50:26.224 --> 00:50:27.265
Good luck with your path.

00:50:31.260 --> 00:50:34.490
So I was in my mid 30s and
I called Amy and I said,

00:50:34.490 --> 00:50:38.740
I need to be considered
someone who does comedy.

00:50:38.740 --> 00:50:40.330
Can I take a class?

00:50:40.330 --> 00:50:41.730
Where do I start?

00:50:41.730 --> 00:50:44.230
And she said, we've
got some shows

00:50:44.230 --> 00:50:49.240
that are designed for actors
to play with our improvisers.

00:50:49.240 --> 00:50:52.030
So I started doing those shows.

00:50:52.030 --> 00:50:54.830
And it was like a
switch had been flipped,

00:50:54.830 --> 00:50:56.220
where they're like oh, you guys!

00:50:56.220 --> 00:50:57.850
Nick Offerman does comedy.

00:50:57.850 --> 00:51:01.930
And suddenly I was allowed
to make people laugh.

00:51:05.860 --> 00:51:07.585
I've still got five.

00:51:07.585 --> 00:51:09.120
AUDIENCE: OK, I'll
make this quick.

00:51:09.120 --> 00:51:10.530
Hi.

00:51:10.530 --> 00:51:13.470
So my husband is from
Stillman Valley, Illinois.

00:51:13.470 --> 00:51:15.192
Loves to build things,
grows hair well.

00:51:15.192 --> 00:51:16.650
[INTERPOSING VOICES]
Sounds badass.

00:51:16.650 --> 00:51:18.420
AUDIENCE: Really polite guy.

00:51:18.420 --> 00:51:20.380
And we've been out
here for seven years.

00:51:20.380 --> 00:51:22.400
We moved here from Chicago,
both theater people.

00:51:22.400 --> 00:51:23.700
Columbia College.

00:51:23.700 --> 00:51:27.015
And how do I keep him from
turning into an LA asshole?

00:51:27.015 --> 00:51:29.140
Like, how do you surround
yourself with like-minded

00:51:29.140 --> 00:51:32.604
people living in this town and--

00:51:32.604 --> 00:51:36.630
NICK OFFERMAN: It's a very
good question, America.

00:51:40.000 --> 00:51:41.800
I'm a great salesman.

00:51:41.800 --> 00:51:44.654
Did you say you went to
theater school at Columbia?

00:51:44.654 --> 00:51:45.570
When did you graduate?

00:51:45.570 --> 00:51:47.700
AUDIENCE: I graduated in '96.

00:51:47.700 --> 00:51:50.941
Sheldon Patinkin was
my director there.

00:51:50.941 --> 00:51:52.144
NICK OFFERMAN: OK.

00:51:52.144 --> 00:51:52.643
'96.

00:51:55.410 --> 00:52:01.690
I taught lighting there
in the department in '95.

00:52:01.690 --> 00:52:04.290
I was in "A Clockwork
Orange" at Steppenwolf.

00:52:04.290 --> 00:52:07.780
I had my whole head shaved, but
just had the front inch of hair

00:52:07.780 --> 00:52:09.414
with a huge red beard.

00:52:09.414 --> 00:52:10.955
AUDIENCE: I would
have remembered you

00:52:10.955 --> 00:52:11.972
if I had your class.

00:52:11.972 --> 00:52:13.638
NICK OFFERMAN: They
called me Faceplate.

00:52:16.002 --> 00:52:18.210
And at the end of one semester
of teaching lighting--

00:52:18.210 --> 00:52:19.880
I used to build
scenery in their shop,

00:52:19.880 --> 00:52:22.350
and they needed somebody to
teach this lighting class.

00:52:22.350 --> 00:52:26.120
I was 25, my students
were like, 22.

00:52:26.120 --> 00:52:27.950
Two of them were
lovely young ladies,

00:52:27.950 --> 00:52:32.900
who I maybe paid a little
too much attention to

00:52:32.900 --> 00:52:34.210
in the classroom.

00:52:34.210 --> 00:52:37.300
And they were just,
like, have you

00:52:37.300 --> 00:52:42.300
done anything, like even
a music video, or like

00:52:42.300 --> 00:52:45.820
do you have nothing
but these plays?

00:52:45.820 --> 00:52:47.170
And I was like, no.

00:52:47.170 --> 00:52:50.510
But they're really good plays.

00:52:50.510 --> 00:52:53.680
Are you familiar
with "The Crucible"?

00:52:53.680 --> 00:52:55.070
It was really weird.

00:52:55.070 --> 00:52:56.600
I was super uncomfortable.

00:52:56.600 --> 00:52:59.300
And people-- my peers
would say, dude.

00:52:59.300 --> 00:53:01.180
I can't believe you,
like, blew that meeting.

00:53:01.180 --> 00:53:03.250
You have to go in
there and be a shark,

00:53:03.250 --> 00:53:09.566
and like, blow your x factor
all over the people interviewing

00:53:09.566 --> 00:53:10.550
you.

00:53:10.550 --> 00:53:17.020
And I was like, I don't
do that to people.

00:53:17.020 --> 00:53:18.046
I don't sell myself.

00:53:18.046 --> 00:53:20.170
I don't want people to hire
me because they thought

00:53:20.170 --> 00:53:23.970
it was cool sitting in their
office to do a job on stage.

00:53:23.970 --> 00:53:27.860
That doesn't make sense to me.

00:53:27.860 --> 00:53:31.630
And all the people that I
saw chasing that, chasing

00:53:31.630 --> 00:53:33.710
the sort of fashion
of the business,

00:53:33.710 --> 00:53:36.950
reading magazines to see, like,
how to get their hair cut,

00:53:36.950 --> 00:53:40.270
and like, try to go
to the right parties,

00:53:40.270 --> 00:53:43.580
trying to find all the ways
by which you might get ahead

00:53:43.580 --> 00:53:50.059
in the business without actually
doing so for the right reasons.

00:53:50.059 --> 00:53:51.600
And I said, I don't
like any of this.

00:53:51.600 --> 00:53:52.690
It's gross.

00:53:52.690 --> 00:53:56.370
So I'm going to step out of it.

00:53:56.370 --> 00:53:59.080
And that's why I gave up
the commercial auditions.

00:53:59.080 --> 00:54:03.720
I gave up trying to act like
people trying to get work here,

00:54:03.720 --> 00:54:07.230
and instead do what
made my life happy up

00:54:07.230 --> 00:54:10.660
until that point, which was
build things with my tools,

00:54:10.660 --> 00:54:14.060
work in theater, even
though nobody comes in LA.

00:54:14.060 --> 00:54:16.790
I found a great theater company
called the Evidence Room,

00:54:16.790 --> 00:54:18.560
and started working with them.

00:54:18.560 --> 00:54:21.470
And that didn't make
me rich or famous,

00:54:21.470 --> 00:54:23.020
but it made me super happy.

00:54:23.020 --> 00:54:27.370
It found me the love of my life.

00:54:27.370 --> 00:54:30.760
And so that's my answer
to your question,

00:54:30.760 --> 00:54:34.380
is to try to avoid
all-- don't look

00:54:34.380 --> 00:54:37.420
for the answer in
any popular culture

00:54:37.420 --> 00:54:40.640
magazines or channels,
because they're usually

00:54:40.640 --> 00:54:42.730
trying to make money--
trying to either sell

00:54:42.730 --> 00:54:46.280
magazines or shoes or
Rogaine or something.

00:54:46.280 --> 00:54:51.415
But instead, it's that
great John Lennon quote of,

00:54:51.415 --> 00:54:53.040
"Your life is what
happens while you're

00:54:53.040 --> 00:54:54.800
busy making other plans."

00:54:54.800 --> 00:54:56.530
I really try to focus on that.

00:54:56.530 --> 00:54:58.930
I come from this wonderful
salt of the earth

00:54:58.930 --> 00:55:02.720
family in Illinois, and
it's a really happy family.

00:55:02.720 --> 00:55:05.290
And so I try to just
maintain my life

00:55:05.290 --> 00:55:07.170
like my family does
in Illinois, which

00:55:07.170 --> 00:55:11.200
is get together with people,
enjoy food and drink,

00:55:11.200 --> 00:55:13.490
make things.

00:55:13.490 --> 00:55:20.410
And the things that
I avoid are like,

00:55:20.410 --> 00:55:25.350
isolationist, like basically
multimedia masturbation,

00:55:25.350 --> 00:55:28.820
where it's so easy
to spend a whole day,

00:55:28.820 --> 00:55:32.500
like, doing all kinds of
things online, or like,

00:55:32.500 --> 00:55:36.239
chasing down somebody from
junior high on Facebook.

00:55:36.239 --> 00:55:36.780
I don't know.

00:55:36.780 --> 00:55:39.420
I found I'm much happier
trying to continue

00:55:39.420 --> 00:55:41.590
to interact with people.

00:55:41.590 --> 00:55:46.630
And I've often said that
it's so much more fun

00:55:46.630 --> 00:55:48.990
to have eight people
with one beer each,

00:55:48.990 --> 00:55:52.620
than to have one person
with eight beers.

00:55:52.620 --> 00:55:54.660
That sounds
wrongheaded, but I've

00:55:54.660 --> 00:55:58.364
crunched the numbers many times.

00:55:58.364 --> 00:56:00.480
And I stand by it.

00:56:00.480 --> 00:56:02.684
I hope that's of
some sort of service.

00:56:02.684 --> 00:56:04.850
INTERVIEWER: All right,
that's all the time we have.

00:56:04.850 --> 00:56:08.720
Thank you again, Nick Offerman
for coming to talk to us.

00:56:08.720 --> 00:56:10.870
NICK OFFERMAN: Thank
you for having me.

